│ optimizer incorrectly applies a condition on an IV in the current iteration to a PHI node that holds the IV's value from the previous iteration. My attempts to patch `ScalarEvolution`  │
│ directly have failed, indicating the logic is more complex than my fixes accounted for. My last attempt to patch `IndVarSimplify.cpp` was also incorrect.                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The most robust solution at this point is to prevent the specific incorrect transformation from happening, without trying to fix the underlying complex reasoning in `ScalarEvolution`.  │
│ The transformation happens in `IndVarSimplify.cpp` when it tries to simplify the `icmp` instruction.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem is that `simplifyICmpInst` is called on `%cmp = icmp sgt i32 %indvar2, 0`. The operand `%indvar2` is a PHI node that `ScalarEvolution` fails to correctly analyze in the     │
│ context of the `for.end` block.                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A targeted fix is to prevent `simplifyICmpInst` from simplifying comparisons involving PHI nodes that are not the primary induction variable being analyzed. The `IVUsers` object tracks │
│ the primary IV. If an operand of the `icmp` is a PHI node but is *not* the primary IV, it's a secondary recurrence like `%indvar2`, which is the source of the problem. We should be     │
│ conservative in this case.                                                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will modify `simplifyICmpInst` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/IndVarSimplify.cpp`. I will add a check at the beginning of the function. If either operand of the `ICmpInst` is a       │
│ `PHINode` and it is not the primary induction variable (`IV->getLoopIV()`), I will return `false`, preventing the simplification. This is a safe, conservative fix that directly targets │
│ the problematic pattern.                                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '/^static bool simplifyICmpInst(ICmpInst \*IC, IVUsers \*IV, SCEVExpander &Rewriter,/a \                                                                                          │
│   if ((isa<PHINode>(IC->getOperand(0)) && IC->getOperand(0) != IV->getLoopIV()) || \                                                                                                     │
